<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="200" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,220,1299]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,1020,1043]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after Jan Ševčík, a specialist on 
<taxonomicName box="[837,917,1020,1043]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
associated with fungi and supervisor of David Kaspřák’s Ph.D. study, who was the first to spot the specimens of the new species in Ulu 
<collectingRegion box="[390,513,1084,1107]" country="Brunei" name="Temburong" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Temburong</collectingRegion>
National Park.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="200" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,220,1299]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,205,1116,1139]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Biology.</emphasis>
The larvae and pupae of the new species were found on the underside of a log over a small brook. The larvae spun a silk sheet over the surface of an unidentified wood encrusting fungus (
<figureCitation box="[203,284,1180,1203]" captionStart="Figs 13–15. 13" captionStartId="6.[150,187,949,968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,930]" captionTargetId="figure-228@6.[148,1129,219,930]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 13–15. 13 – The larvae of Leptomorphus sevciki sp. nov. on the surface of an unidentified wood encrusting fungus growing on a log in a rainforest in Brunei. 14 – The pupae of L. sevciki sp. nov., on the underside of a log in a rainforest in Brunei. 15 – The fallen tree over a pathway with hanging pupae in Ulu Temburong National Park in Brunei. (Photos: J. Ševčík)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315600/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
, Video: https://youtu.be/89HN2255ZOs). The pupae were hanging from a singly anchored 
<quantity box="[291,372,1212,1235]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" unit="cm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 cm</quantity>
long yellowish thread, bearing a drop of brownish liquid (
<figureCitation box="[1004,1084,1212,1235]" captionStart="Figs 13–15. 13" captionStartId="6.[150,187,949,968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,930]" captionTargetId="figure-228@6.[148,1129,219,930]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 13–15. 13 – The larvae of Leptomorphus sevciki sp. nov. on the surface of an unidentified wood encrusting fungus growing on a log in a rainforest in Brunei. 14 – The pupae of L. sevciki sp. nov., on the underside of a log in a rainforest in Brunei. 15 – The fallen tree over a pathway with hanging pupae in Ulu Temburong National Park in Brunei. (Photos: J. Ševčík)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5315600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5315600/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
, Video: https://youtu.be/89HN2255ZOs). The behaviour of the flying adults and their colouration were reminiscent of wasps or ichneumonids (Hymenoptera).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
